{{Spanish name|Samaranch|Salisachs}}

'''Juan Antonio Samaranch Salisachs''' (born November 1, 1959) is the son of [[Juan Antonio Samaranch|Juan Antonio i Samaranch]] (former president of the [[International Olympic Committee]]) and his late wife, Bibi Salisachs. He is married and has four children. He has a [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] degree from [[New York University]] and a degree in industrial engineering from [[Universitat Politècnica de Catalunya]], [[Spain]].

In 1986 he joined as an associate of [[Credit Suisse First Boston|The First Boston Corporation]], in New York, until 1989. He was appointed that year to the vice-presidency, in the Corporate Finance area, at the English firm S.G. Warburg & Co. At the present, he is the CEO of [[GBS Finanzas]], S.A. Before obtaining his MBA, he worked at [[International Flavors and Fragrances]], as an accounting executive. He is fluent in English, Spanish, French, Italian and [[Catalan language|Catalan]].

He is a member of the [[International Olympic Committee]] since 2001, representing Spain. He's also a member of the Spanish Olympic Committee<ref>http://www.munimadrid.es/UnidadesDescentralizadas/UDCMedios/noticias/2005/07_Julio/06/Files/JUAN%20A%20SAMARANCHA%202%208%20JUNIO.PDF{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Muni Madrid</ref> and first vice-president of the [[Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne|International Modern Pentathlon Union]] since 1996.

==Controversies==

===Scholarship controversy===
The controversial figure of his father also affected his own life: while his father was president of the Spanish savings bank [[La Caixa]], he got a scholarship to complete his MBA at [[New York University]] from the private foundation of this bank.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}

===Wrestling exclusion from the Olympics===
In February 2013 the IOC voted to eliminate a single sport from the Olympics. Although many experts predicted that the pentathlon would be removed<ref>{{cite web|title=IOC to Drop One Sport: Pentathlon in the Hot Seat|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=171840100|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 8, 2013|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> due to its low popularity. Instead, wrestling was voted to be removed, despite having a larger athlete and fan base. Many cited Samaranch-Salisachs's influence to explain the IOCs reasoning.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=171840100|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 13, 2013|title=Body Slam For Wrestling: Sport Cut From Olympics|accessdate=February 13, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-juan-antonio-samaranch-modern-pentathlon-20130212,0,1157345.story|author=Houston Mitchell|title=Former IOC president's son is modern pentathlon vice president|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 13, 2013|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> On 8 September 2013, the IOC announced that wrestling would remain part of the Summer Olympics, reversing the February decision.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-08/wrestling-wins-vote-to-retain-spot-in-2020-summer-olympic-games IOC Reinstates Wrestling as Olympic Sport for 2020, 2024 Games]</ref>

