[[File:Lydia K. Aholo, 1897.jpg|thumb|Lydia Aholo in the graduating class [[Kamehameha Schools|Kamehameha School]] for Girls in 1897]]
'''Lydia Kaʻonohiponiponiokalani Aholo''' (February 6, 1878 – July 7, 1979) was the namesake and ''[[hānai]]'' daughter of Queen [[Liliuokalani|Liliʻuokalani]] of [[Hawai'i]]. She became an educator and was the first to formally teach [[Hawaiian language]] at [[Kamehameha Schools]].
==Biography== Aholo was born on February 6, 1878, in [[Lahaina]], [[Maui]]. Her parents were Keahi Aholo, who died shortly after the birth, and [[Luther Aholo]], who would become a leading politician in the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]] and secretary at the time to [[Governors of Maui|Governor of Maui]] [[John Owen Dominis]], husband of the future Queen [[Liliuokalani|Liliʻuokalani]]. The girl was the Aholos' third child, and there were many siblings from her father's previous marriage.
Dominis and Liliʻuokalani's marriage had been childless, and she had decided to adopt the newborn child as her own under the Hawaiian tradition of ''[[hānai]]'' despite the disapproval of her husband, her mother-in-law and her brother King [[Kalākaua]].{{sfn|Allen|1982|pages=149–152}} She named her Lydia Kaʻonohiponiponiokalani Aholo. Besides Lydia, Liliʻuokalani also adopted [[Joseph Kaiponohea ʻAeʻa]] and [[John ʻAimoku Dominis]].{{sfn|Bonura|Witmer|2013|pages=109–115}}
She grew up in the royal household with her ''hānai'' mother and ''hānai'' brothers. She attended Kawaiaha‘o Female Seminary and graduated from the [[Kamehameha Schools|Kamehameha School]] for Girls in 1897. Aholo also attended [[Oberlin College]], where she studied music. In Queen Liliʻuokalani's old age, Aholo became a confidante to her ''hānai'' mother.{{sfn|Bonura|Witmer|2013|pages=131–37}}
She worked with Principal Ida May Pope at Kamehameha School and taught [[Hawaiian language]] until her retirement at the age of 75.<ref name="OlaNaIwi">{{cite web|author=|title=Aholo, Lydia Kaonohiponiponiokalani|series=Ola Nā Iwi: Kūpuna Project|website=Ka‘iwakīloumoku Virtual Archive, Kamehameha Schools|url=https://apps.ksbe.edu/kaiwakiloumoku/ola-na-iwi/aholo|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref>
Despite never marrying or having her own children, Aholo was devoted to her extended family. In later life, she became a mother figure to her grandniece and grandnephews who called her ''Aunty Tūtū.'' She had a strong influence on her grandnephew [[Alfred Apaka]], a baritone singer who popularized romantic Hawaiian ballads during the 1950s.<ref name="OlaNaIwi"/>
In 1969, Helen G. Allen interviewed the aging Aholo at the Maunalani Hospital in [[Kaimuki, Hawaii|Kaimuki]]. Allen would use the tapes from the interviews to write her 1982 book ''The Betrayal of Liliuokalani''. Parts of the tapes were rediscovered in 2008 by historian Sandra Bonura.<ref name="Gordon2011">{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Mike|title=Lydia's Voice: A long-gone audiotape of royal remembrances by the hanai daughter of Queen Liliuokalani is rediscovered|url=http://www.sandrabonura.com/__honolulu_star_advertiser___116839.htm|date=December 18, 2011|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|location=Honolulu|publisher=Oahu Publications, Inc.|accessdate=July 3, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815064411/http://www.sandrabonura.com/__honolulu_star_advertiser___116839.htm|archivedate=August 15, 2016|df=}}</ref> Aholo died on July 7, 1979, at the age of 101. She was buried at Nuʻuanu Memorial Park.{{sfn|Bonura|Witmer|2013|pages=140–42}}
