{{Infobox person | name = Scott Thorson | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|1|23|mf=yes}} | birth_place = [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]], United States | death_date = | death_place = | education = | occupation = | partner = [[Liberace]] <small>(1976–1982)</small> | children = | parents = | residence = [[Northern Nevada Correctional Center]], [[Carson City, Nevada]], United States | other_names = Jess Marlow |}}
'''Scott Thorson''' (born January 23, 1959, [[La Crosse, Wisconsin]])<ref>{{cite book|title=Behind the Candelabra — My Life with Liberace|authors= Thorson, Scott & Thorliefson, Alex|page= 47|date= 1988|publisher= E.P. Dutton Publishing|isbn= 0-525-24653-3}}</ref> is an [[Americans|American]] best known for his relationship with and lawsuit against the entertainer [[Liberace]].
==Liberace==
=== Relationship === A teenaged Thorson met Liberace in 1976 through his romantic friendship with dancer Bob Street (a friend of [[Hollywood]] producer [[Ray Arnett]]) who was staging Liberace's shows in Vegas. When Thorson was 18, Liberace hired him to act as his personal friend and companion, a position that allegedly included a five-year romantic relationship with lavish gifts, travel, and Liberace's promises that he would adopt and care for Thorson. Liberace claimed that he had "more mink coats and diamonds than Elizabeth Taylor".<ref name="Mashable" /> Liberace also incorporated Thorson into his [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] stage performances – for example, Thorson drove Liberace's [[List of Rolls-Royce motor cars|Rolls-Royce]] onstage,<ref name="transcripts" /> and was a dancer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-03-16/local/me-1065_1_entertainer-liberace|title=Local News in Brief: Liberace Companion Held|author=Metro Digest|date=16 March 1988|journal=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>
According to Thorson, their committed relationship ended because of Liberace's promiscuous behavior and Thorson's drug addiction. Thorson also claimed that it was Liberace that originally started him on the drugs, but then when his habit got out of control, Liberace cut him off from all of his credit cards.<ref name="Mashable">Oprah: Where Are They Now? -Interview with Scott Thorson [TV Series]. (2013). United States: OWN TV (Oprah Winfrey Network).</ref> Thorson stated that following his plastic surgery, the surgeon provided for him a cocktail of highly addictive drugs that included [[cocaine]], [[Methaqualone|Quaalude]]s, biphetamines, and [[Demerol]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/12/fashion/scott-thorson-the-boy-toys-story.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=The Boy Toy’s Story|author=David Segal|date=2013-05-10}}</ref> Thorson stated that since he was so young at the time of meeting Liberace, he would do anything that he could to please him, including getting plastic surgery so that he could resemble him, but he felt that their relationship was one-sided. He called Liberace both generous and possessive.<ref name="Mashable" />
In 2000, Thorson was among several people featured in the British television documentary ''Liberace: Too Much of a Good Thing Is Wonderful''. In 2002, Thorson was interviewed by [[Larry King]] on ''[[Larry King Live]]'', during which Thorson confirmed that, in the midst of his relationship with Liberace, he chose to have plastic surgery to look more like Liberace at the pianist's suggestion. Also during the interview with King, Thorson revealed his chin implant had been removed earlier in 2002.<ref name="transcripts" />
Following his release from prison in 2012, Thorson gave interviews about his relationship with Liberace, one with [[Howard Stern]], in June 2013, in which he talked about former lovers and affairs he had when he lived with Liberace. Another interview was on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' in May 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/121296_Liberace_s_Former_Lover_Details_Secret_Romance|title=Liberace's Former Lover Details Secret Romance|publisher=ETonline.com|accessdate=2013-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.howardstern.com/howard-on-air/howard-100-101/2013-06-17#gallery-20547|title=Gallery|date=June 17, 2013|website=HowardStern.com}}</ref> where he stated that memories of his time with Liberace were still difficult for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbspressexpress.com/cbs-television-distribution/releases/view?id=35339|title=Press Express|publisher=Cbspressexpress.com|accessdate=2013-06-02}}</ref>
===Lawsuit and book === In 1982, after he was let go by Liberace,<ref name="news.google.com">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lPgjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=L2MEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7055,2894925&dq=liberace+denied+homosexual&hl=en Liberace had last laugh on critics by 'crying all the way to the bank'] ''The Pittsburgh Press'', February 5, 1987</ref> Thorson filed a $113 million lawsuit against Liberace,<ref name="celeblegalissues">{{cite web|work=Celeb Legal Issues|title=Celebrity Alimony/Palimony|url=http://www.celeblegalissues.com/legal-jargon/celebrity-alimony-palimony/ }}</ref><ref name="transcripts">{{cite news|journal=Larry King Live|title=Interview with Scott Thorson (Transcript)|date=August 12, 2002 |publisher=CNN|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0208/12/lkl.00.html|accessdate=December 29, 2012}}</ref> part of which was a [[palimony]] suit. This was the first same-sex palimony case filed in U.S. history.<ref name="Mashable" /> Thorson decided to sue because he claimed that Liberace threw him out on the streets with nothing.<ref name="Mashable" /> Liberace continued to deny that he was homosexual, and during court depositions in 1984, he insisted that Thorson was never his lover.{{cn|date=December 2017}} Throughout their lawsuit, Thorson stated that Liberace referred to him in the media as a disgruntled employee, a liar, a gold digger, and claimed that there was never a sexual relationship between them.<ref name="Mashable" />
The case was settled out of court in 1986, with Thorson receiving a $75,000 cash settlement, plus three cars and three pet dogs worth another $20,000.<ref name="news.google.com" /><ref name="Mashable" /> Thorson visited and reconciled with Liberace shortly before the entertainer's death in February 1987.<ref name="transcripts" /> Thorson said, after Liberace had died, that he settled because he knew that Liberace was dying, and that Thorson had intended to sue based on conversion of property rather than palimony.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
A year after Liberace's death, Thorson published a book about their relationship, ''[[Behind the Candelabra: My Life with Liberace]].''<ref name="PM">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/depression-2-0-sunday-in-kerouac-alley-2496025179.html|title=Depression 2.0: Sunday in Kerouac Alley|work=[[PopMatters]]|authorlink=Rodger Jacobs|author=Jacobs, Rodger|date=May 29, 2009}}</ref>
In the Canada–US [[television film]] ''[[Liberace: Behind the Music]]'' (1988), Thorson was portrayed by [[Michael Dolan]].<ref name="MattDamon">{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2010/jul/04/matt-damon-looking-forward-playing-liberaces-lover|title=Matt Damon looking forward to playing Liberace’s lover in upcoming biopic|author=Katsilometes, John|publisher=Lasvegassun.com|accessdate=2013-06-02}}</ref>
Thorson's book was later adapted by [[Richard LaGravenese]] and [[Steven Soderbergh]] into the 2013 film ''[[Behind the Candelabra]]'', in which Thorson was played by [[Matt Damon]] opposite [[Michael Douglas]] as Liberace. The movie aired on [[Home Box Office|HBO]] on May 26, 2013.<ref name="USATodayLiberace">{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2011/10/douglas-damon-starring-in-hbos-liberace-biopic/1|title=Douglas, Damon starring in HBO's Liberace biopic|date=2011-10-11|publisher=Content.usatoday.com|accessdate=2013-06-02}}</ref> The film was directed by [[Steven Soderbergh]] from a screenplay by [[Richard LaGravenese]], with music by Academy Award-winning composer [[Marvin Hamlisch]].<ref name="Marvin">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q35YHvlGJb4&feature=fvst|title=Director Steven Soderbergh on new Liberace film|author=|date=2009-11-20|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2013-06-02}}</ref>
==Other== In 1989, Thorson emerged as a pivotal witness in the prosecution of gangster [[Eddie Nash]], in the [[Wonderland murders|1981 quadruple murders]] of the [[Wonderland Gang]]. For his testimony, he was placed in the federal witness protection program. In 1990, he was shot five times when drug dealers broke into his hotel room in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}
In 2008, Thorson pleaded guilty to felony drug and burglary charges and was sentenced to four years in prison.<ref name="celeblegalissues" />
Previously diagnosed with [[hepatitis C]], in the autumn of 2012 Thorson was diagnosed with [[Cancer staging|stage II]] cancer.<ref name="transcripts" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/story/liberace.s-ex.lover-claims-gay-affair-with-jackson|work=Contactmusic.com|date=2004-04-15|title=Liberace's Ex-Lover Claims Gay Affair With Jackson}}</ref> Since his diagnosis, Thorson has made public pleas for money to continue his medical treatments. Thorson had planned in 2012 to re-release the book ''Behind the Candelabra'' to coincide with the film's release.<ref>{{cite news|title=EXCLUSIVE: Inside Scott Thorson's Cancer Battle|author=Staff|url=https://www.etonline.com/news/126245_EXCLUSIVE_Inside_Scott_Thorson_Cancer_Battle|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=2012-10-25|accessdate=2013-05-04}}</ref>
In February 2013, police investigating a lost wallet tracked the use of the victim's credit cards to a hotel in [[Reno, Nevada]]. Thorson was found to be using the credit cards and was arrested. Thorson (who also uses the alias '''Jess Marlow''', an alias he says that he acquired when he entered the protection program in the Nash case) was booked on a variety of charges, including burglary and using a credit card without consent.<ref name="The Boy Toy's Story">{{cite news|last=Segal|first=David|title=The Boy Toy's Story|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/12/fashion/scott-thorson-the-boy-toys-story.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynews4.com/mostpopular/story/Liberaces-Alleged-Ex-Lover-in-Washoe-County-Jail/3HFiMUhk0kW59dVYRjVTjg.cspx|title=Liberace's Alleged Ex-Lover in Washoe County Jail|work=My News 4|publisher=[[KRNV-DT]]|date=2013-05-28|accessdate=2013-06-02}}</ref> He pleaded guilty and was sentenced to five years' probation in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radaronline.com/exclusives/2013/07/liberace-lover-scott-thorson-sentenced-stolen-credit-card|title=Liberace's Ex-Lover Scott Thorson Sentenced To 5 Years Probation After Using Stolen Credit Cards|publisher=Radaronline.com|accessdate=2013-07-18}}</ref>
Thorson did not do well on probation. In September 2013, he tested positive for [[methamphetamine]], but was given another chance. He subsequently failed drug tests again — twice in October, and again on November 1, 2013. He was arrested on November 19, 2013, after violating a court order to enter an inpatient treatment facility in Reno two weeks earlier. On January 23, 2014, his probation was revoked and he was sentenced to 8 to 20 years in Nevada prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/01/23/liberace-lover-to-spend-8-to-20-years-in-prison/4806535|title=Liberace's lover Scott Thorson sentenced to prison|author=AP|date=January 23, 2014|work=USA TODAY}}</ref> Thorson is currently incarcerated in [[Northern Nevada Correctional Center]] in [[Carson City, Nevada|Carson City]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}
[[Dennis Hof]], owner of several legal Nevada brothels and the one who bailed Thorson out of jail during some of his 2013 legal problems, <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalenquirer.com/true-crime/exclusive-liberace-ex-lover-scott-thorson-sentenced-prison|title=Former Liberace lover Scott Thorson living at Bunny Ranch|author=UPI|date=10 June 2013}}</ref> had said that this long prison sentence, because of Thorson's cancer, is a "virtual death sentence."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalenquirer.com/true-crime/exclusive-liberace-ex-lover-scott-thorson-sentenced-prison/|title=EXCLUSIVE! LIBERACE EX -LOVER SCOTT THORSON SENTENCED TO PRISON|date=2014-01-23|work=National Enquirer|access-date=2018-01-06|language=en-US}}</ref>
