{{One source|date=August 2015}} [[File:Simplício Rodrigues de Sá - Retrato de Dom João VI.jpg|thumb|200px|Portrait of King [[João VI]] (c.1820).]] [[File:DpedroI-brasil-full.jpg|thumb|200px|Portrait of Emperor [[Pedro I of Brazil|Pedro I]] (c.1830).]] '''Simplício Rodrigues de Sá''' (1785, [[São Nicolau Tolentino (São Domingos)|São Nicolau Tolentino]], [[Cape Verde]], — 9 March 1839, [[Rio de Janeiro]]) was a Portuguese-born painter and art professor who spent most of his career in Brazil.
==Biography== Simplício Rodrigues de Sá was born in the parish of [[São Nicolau Tolentino (São Domingos)|São Nicolau Tolentino]] (now part of the municipality of [[São Domingos, Cape Verde (municipality)|São Domingos]]) just north of the city of [[Praia]] in the island of [[Santiago, Cape Verde|Santiago]]
He studied in Lisbon and emigrated to Rio de Janeiro in Brazil in 1809. Seven years later, he became a follower of [[Jean Baptiste Debret]], joining his group, the [[Missão Artística Francesa|French Artistic Mission]] and helping to lay the foundations for what would become the [[Academia Imperial de Belas Artes]] in 1826.<ref name="I">[http://www.itaucultural.org.br/aplicexternas/enciclopedia_ic/index.cfm?fuseaction=artistas_biografia&cd_verbete=931&cd_idioma=28555&cd_item=1 Brief biographies] @ the Enciclopédia Itaú Cultural.</ref>
He was also named a [[court painter]] and a private art tutor to Princess [[Maria da Glória]], the future Queen of Portugal. For his services, Emperor Pedro I awarded him the [[Order of Christ (Brazil)|Order of Christ]] in 1826, and named him a Knight in the [[Order of the Southern Cross]].<ref name="I" /> In 1831, when Debret returned to Paris, De Sá took his place as head of the History Painting Department at the Imperial Academy.
In 1833, he became drawing master for the child-Emperor [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro II]] and his sisters. After the death of {{ill|Henrique José da Silva|pt|Henrique José da Silva (pintor)}} in 1834, he took over the Department of Design at the Academy. He also organized the first two major public exhibitions held there, in 1829 and 1830, although his first solo exhibition appears to have been given posthumously.<ref name="I" />
He worked in several genres, including religious works for the Church of the "Ordem Terceira de São Francisco da Penitência", but is largely remembered as a portrait painter who focused on members of the [[Imperial Family of Brazil|Royal Family]]. He was apparently blind at the time of his death.<ref name="I" />
